<DOC><DOCNO> AP890405-0188 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-89 1829EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-05 0533</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0546</SECOND><HEAD>Thunder In Florida, Rain Along The East Coast</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Wet weather spread over much of the East on Wednesday, whilehigh wind blew across the central Rockies and southern Californiahad another unusually hot day with temperatures of 100 and more.   Showers were scattered ahead of a cold front that stretched fromsouthern New England across the middle Atlantic Coast states to theFlorida Panhandle.   Strong thunderstorms developed in warm, moist, unstable air overthe central Florida Peninsula.   Heavier rainfall during the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT included0.73 of an inch at Panama City, Fla.   Very cold, unstable air over the Great Lakes contributed to thedevelopment of showers across that region. Hail the size of peasfell west of Springfield, Ill.   High wind blew over the central Rockies. In western Wyoming,wind gusted to near 70 mph at Crowheart.   The wind created blowing-snow conditions across sections of theColorado Rockies, where as much as 6 feet of snow had fallen byWednesday from a storm that stalled for a week. Some ski resortsconsidered extending their seasons.   Light rain fell over the northern Rockies and along the coast ofWashington state.   Also in the Northwest, warming weather was blamed for anavalanche that covered all four lanes of U.S. 2 at Stevens Pass inWashington's Cascade Mountains early Wednesday. There were noinjuries and one lane was reopened by midday.   Sections of southern California and the desert Southwest hadreadings in the 90s and above. By midday, downtown Los Angeles hadreached 96 degrees and Santa Ana sizzled at 100 degrees.   On Tuesday, Los Angeles hit a record 100 degrees and Los AngelesCounty lifeguards telephoned reserves for extra help, adding dozensof lifeguards to monitor an estimated 100,000 beachgoers.   The unseasonably warm weather was a result of an upper levelhigh pressure system off the southern California coast. But theSanta Ana winds that began Sunday and ushered in the Apriltemperatures began diminishing Wednesday, allowing smog to invadethe region.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 33degrees at Marquette, Mich., to 104 at Ontario, Calif. Wednesday'slow in the Lower 48 states was 14 degrees at Alamosa, Colo.   For Thursday, showers and some thunderstorms were forecast fromeastern sections of the middle Atlantic Coast states to NewEngland. Scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast over thenorthern Plains and southern sections of the upper MississippiValley. Rain also was forecast from coastal Washington state towestern Montana.   Highs in the 30s were predicted from northeastern Minnesota toUpper Michigan; in the 40s and 50s from the coast of Washingtonstate across the northern Rockies, the northern Plains andNebraska, much of the upper and middle Mississippi Valley, theGreat Lakes, the Ohio Valley and all of the Appalachians to NewEngland; in the 80s over the southern Florida Peninsula, and fromsouth-central and southwestern Texas across southern New Mexico andwestern Nevada to the central Pacific Coast; in the 90s acrosssouthern Arizona and southern California; above 100 across thedesert Southwest; and generally in the 60s and 70s over theremainder of the nation.</TEXT></DOC>